SHEET 2 — RIM SECTIONS
Purpose
The rim sections are the fundamental building blocks of the RAMA Hub. Each one is a fully self-contained structural module designed for mass production, easy transport, and rapid orbital assembly.

Module Geometry
Dimensions: 15m × 20m footprint

Height: 15m

Quantity: 20 identical units

Shape: Slightly curved to form a 400m circumference ring when assembled

Mass: Optimized for single-launch delivery per section

Design Principles
Absolute uniformity: Every rim section is identical — no variants, no exceptions

Pure structure: No embedded systems, no utilities, no mission-specific hardware

Load-bearing: Designed to handle:

Hub compression forces

Attachment loads from MOEs, factories, and support systems

Long-term orbital stress cycles

Construction simplicity: Every rim section is built entirely from just three L‑bracket sizes and standardized cable assemblies.  
This keeps manufacturing cheap, modular, and globally reproducible.

Manufacturing Logic
Built on Earth using standard industrial processes

No exotic materials required

Designed for:

Fast fabrication

Easy inspection

Predictable tolerances

Low-cost replication

Assembly Behavior
Each section includes:

Standardized connection points

Alignment guides

MOE-friendly docking geometry

When all 20 are joined, the ring becomes a rigid, stable, self-correcting structure

Why This Matters
Identical rim sections give RAMA:

Predictable mass and geometry

Simplified logistics

Reduced cost

Extreme modularity

The ability to scale to larger rings simply by increasing section count
